I get why it feels that way. A lot of consumer apps are tuned for engagement and revenue, and that can drift away from what users actually want. It doesn’t have to be that way—but fixing it means changing the incentives, not just the features.

⸻

What’s really going on (under the hood)

Most platforms optimize for a few measurable targets:
	•	time spent
	•	daily/weekly active users
	•	conversion (subscriptions, ads)

Those are easy to measure and monetize, so they become the “north star.”
But they’re proxies, not the true outcome.

For dating, the true outcome is something like:

“Did this person form a healthy, durable connection?”

That’s harder to measure, slower to observe, and paradoxical (success often means you leave the app). So many apps default to what’s measurable, not what’s meaningful.

⸻

If you wanted a system that actually helps people pair up

You’d redesign around different objectives and metrics:

1) Change the objective function

Instead of:
	•	maximize swipes, matches, time-on-app

Use:
	•	pair formation rate (matches that convert to real dates)
	•	relationship durability (30/90/180-day check-ins)
	•	user-reported well-being (did this improve your life?)

Those are slower signals, but they align with the mission.

⸻

2) Build for fewer, better matches
	•	limit daily intros (e.g., 3–5 high-quality candidates)
	•	show why someone is a fit (shared constraints, values, rhythms)
	•	highlight likely friction points up front

Think briefs, not feeds.

⸻

3) Use AI as an advisor, not a manipulator
	•	summarize compatibility and tradeoffs
	•	surface patterns from your past (“you tend to pick X and regret Y”)
	•	offer conversation starters tailored to both people

But keep the human in control of the final decision.

⸻

4) Align incentives with outcomes

A few viable models:
	•	subscription that pauses when you’re in an active match
	•	success fee / referral credit when users confirm a stable relationship
	•	co-op or user-owned model where value flows back to users
	•	strict data governance (consent, portability, minimal retention)

If revenue grows when users succeed (and even when they leave), the product stops fighting them.

⸻

5) Add guardrails
	•	transparency: show what data is used and why
	•	bias checks: audit matching for unfair patterns
	•	security: strong protections against manipulation
	•	opt-outs and controls at every step

⸻

A simple “AI court for dating” flow
	1.	Profile (explicit + behavioral): values, lifestyle, dealbreakers
	2.	Candidate set: small, curated pool
	3.	Brief: compatibility, likely strengths, likely conflicts
	4.	Decision: you accept/decline
	5.	Feedback loop: outcomes update the model
	6.	Off-ramp: if a connection sticks, the app steps back

⸻

One honest caveat

Even with better incentives, there’s a tension:
	•	optimization vs. discovery

If you optimize too hard, you can:
	•	overfit to your past
	•	miss unexpected-but-great matches

So a good system keeps a slice for exploration, not just “best predicted fit.”

